The best thing to do when entering prompts into a language model is to be as specific as you can about what you have in mind.

It can take some experience knowing what to put in the prompt, but the general requirements are pretty simple. Consider these key questions as you design your Medium-level app:

* What is the app used to do?  
* What do you want the app to look like?  
* How should the user click, drag, or type into the app? How should the app respond?  
* What should the app store for the user or save? If you are entering data into the app, you want to save it somewhere so that you don't have to re-enter it each time you run it. We recommend using localStorage for browser-based persistence.  
* What does the app do to process the data you enter into it, if any? Should it sort by date? Tell you which item you've entered is coming up next in the calendar? For Medium complexity, aim for straightforward data processing that accomplishes a clear educational purpose. Anything that involves getting different websites to talk to each other, as well as searching or optimizing arrangements of data…that might require a lot more work and development to get it to work. Look at the Advanced tab for some examples of this.  
* Does your app require any use of AI? If AI functionality is needed, you'll require an API key from a language model provider. Include instructions for where to paste this key in your app design.
